.TH CP(1),User Commands,CP(1)

.SH NAME
cp - copy files

.SH SYNOPSIS
cp [-h] [--] source dest

cp [-h] [--] source ... directory

.SH DESCRIPTION
cp copies each source file to dest.
In the two-operand form, source is copied to dest.
If more than two operands are given, the last operand must be an existing directory and each source is copied into it, keeping its basename.

If the final operand is not a directory and more than two operands are given, cp prints an error and exits without copying.

.SH OPTIONS
-h: Print a short usage summary and exit 0.

--: End of options. Subsequent arguments are treated as filenames even if they begin with -.

.SH DIAGNOSTICS
cp: missing file operand - no arguments were given.

cp: missing destination file operand after 'X' - only one operand was given.

cp: target 'X' is not a directory - more than two operands were given but the final one is not a directory.

cp: source file 'X' does not exist - a named source could not be opened.

cp: unable to copy file 'X' to path 'Y' - the copy operation failed.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: All files copied successfully.

1: Usage error or at least one copy failed.

.SH EXAMPLES
Copy one file:

$ cp a.txt b.txt

Copy multiple files into a directory:

$ cp README Makefile /tmp/
